.rgmdl is the extension for the rat game model format but like
nobody really cares so use whatever you want.
it's got a few parts to it: a model, a texture, and a texture
map.
models and textures are denoted with a filepath like so:
model = asdf;
texture = asdf;
whitespace before and after the = operator is trimmed but
everything between the first non-whitespace character and the
semicolon is taken as the file name. no fancy stuff like
globbing and you only get to set it once per model (once per
file).
the texture map is assigned as [(x,y),(x,y),(x,y)...] where x
and y are floating point numbers. it represents the uv
coordinates of each triangle on the model's vertex, in the
same order as in the model. you can have up to as many
vertices as there are on the model (including overlaps)
there are also a few functions (i'll probably add more later)
that help out with making the texture map because its pretty
annoying to do manually and they are:
- texmap_offset(x,y)
    shifts every assigned point on the map by (x,y) where x
    and y are floats.
- texmap_scale(x,y)
    transforms each assigned point by (x0,y0)->(x0*x,y0*y). i
    can't say multiples because there's like 5 products. x and
    y are floats.
- texmap_filldefault(a,b)
    a and b are x, y, or z. fills in all unassigned points on
    the texture map with the value of their mesh-space
    counterpart. example: texmap_filldefault(z,x) sets all
    unassigned points's x to their counterpart's z and their y
    to their counterpart's x.
